    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "that makes sense. so they basically just swarm the area and attack whatever they find. is there any specific pattern to how they move or how they coordinate the attack on a large group of bacteria? like do they act more independently or is there some sort of signaling that makes them move like a unit?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "While they exhibit individual phagocytic actions, their recruitment is highly coordinated via chemokines released by damaged tissues and resident immune cells. These chemoattractants create a concentration gradient, effectively guiding the \"swarm\" of neutrophils to the site of highest inflammation. This movement, called chemotaxis, ensures a directed and concentrated response rather than a random scattering. Essentially, the signals act as a map directing the collective force of immune cells.",
